==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wave
<hw>Wave</hw> <pr>(w⟦amac⟧v)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>See
<er>Waive</er>.</def> <rj><au>Sir H. Wotton.</au>
<au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wave
<hw>Wave</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Waved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Waving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>waven</ets>, AS.
<ets>wafian</ets> to waver, to hesitate, to wonder; akin to
<ets>w⟦ae⟧fre</ets> wavering, restless, MHG. <ets>wabern</ets> to be in
motion, Icel. <ets>vafra</ets> to hover about; cf. Icel.
<ets>v⟦amac⟧fa</ets> to vibrate. Cf. <er>Waft</er>,
<er>Waver</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To play loosely; to move like a wave, one way and
the other; to float; to flutter; to undulate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His purple robes <qex>waved</qex> careless to the winds.</q>
<rj><qau>Trumbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the flags of three nations has successively
<qex>waved</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be moved to and fro as a signal.</def> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fluctuate; to waver; to be in an unsettled state;
to vacillate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>waved</qex> indifferently 'twixt doing them neither good
nor harm.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wave
<hw>Wave</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move one way and the
other; to brandish.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧[Aeneas] <xex>waved</xex> his fatal
sword.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise into inequalities of surface; to give an
undulating form a surface to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Horns whelked and <qex>waved</qex> like the enridged sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move like a wave, or by floating; to waft.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To call attention to, or give a direction or command
to, by a waving motion, as of the hand; to signify by waving; to beckon;
to signal; to indicate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Look, with what courteous action⟦br⟧
It <qex>waves</qex> you to a more removed ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She spoke, and bowing <qex>waved</qex>⟦br⟧
Dismissal.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wave</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wave
<hw>Wave</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Wave</er>, <pos>v.</pos>;
not the same word as OE. <ets>wawe</ets>, <ets>waghe</ets>, a wave,
which is akin to E. <ets>wag</ets> to move. ⟦root⟧138. See
<er>Wave</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An advancing ridge or swell on the surface of a
liquid, as of the sea, resulting from the oscillatory motion of the
particles composing it when disturbed by any force their position of
rest; an undulation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>wave</qex> behind impels the <qex>wave</qex> before.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>A vibration propagated from
particle to particle through a body or elastic medium, as in the
transmission of sound; an assemblage of vibrating molecules in all
phases of a vibration, with no phase repeated; a wave of vibration; an
undulation. See <er>Undulation</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Water; a body of water.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Deep drank Lord Marmion of the <xex>wave</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Build a ship to save thee from the flood,⟦br⟧
I 'll furnish thee with fresh <qex>wave</qex>, bread, and wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Unevenness; inequality of surface.</def> <rj><au>Sir
I. Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A waving or undulating motion; a signal made with
the hand, a flag, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The undulating line or streak of luster on cloth
watered, or calendered, or on damask steel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Something resembling or likened to a water wave, as
in rising unusually high, in being of unusual extent, or in progressive
motion; a swelling or excitement, as of feeling or energy; a tide;
flood; period of intensity, usual activity, or the like; <as>as, a
<ex>wave</ex> of enthusiasm; <ex>waves</ex> of applause</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wave front</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <cd>the
surface of initial displacement of the particles in a medium, as a wave
of vibration advances.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave length</b></col>
<fld>(Physics)</fld>, <cd>the space, reckoned in the direction of
propagation, occupied by a complete wave or undulation, as of light,
sound, etc.; the distance from a point or phase in a wave to the nearest
point at which the same phase occurs.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave
line</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>a line of a vessel's hull,
shaped in accordance with the wave-line system.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Wave-line system</b></col>, <col><b>Wave-line
theory</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>a system or
theory of designing the lines of a vessel, which takes into
consideration the length and shape of a wave which travels at a certain
speed.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave loaf</b></col>, <cd>a loaf for a wave
offering.</cd> <au>Lev. viii. 27.</au> -- <col><b>Wave moth</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of small geometrid
moths belonging to <gen>Acidalia</gen> and allied genera; -- so called
from the wavelike color markings on the wings.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave
offering</b></col>, <cd>an offering made in the Jewish services by
waving the object, as a loaf of bread, toward the four cardinal
points.</cd> <au>Num. xviii. 11.</au> -- <col><b>Wave of
vibration</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>, <cd>a wave which consists in,
or is occasioned by, the production and transmission of a vibratory
state from particle to particle through a body.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave
surface</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <cd>A surface of
simultaneous and equal displacement of the particles composing a wave of
vibration.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <cd>A mathematical
surface of the fourth order which, upon certain hypotheses, is the locus
of a wave surface of light in the interior of crystals. It is used in
explaining the phenomena of double refraction. See under
<er>Refraction</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Wave theory</b></col>.
<fld>(Physics)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Undulatory theory</cref>, under
<er>Undulatory</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waved</ent>⟦br⟧
